\begin{problem}{2.a}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
Assume without loss to contradiction that $a > b$. Then, note that an ideal containing $X^a - 1, X^b - 1$ also contains $X^a - 1 - (X^b - 1)(X^{a - b}) = X^{a - b} - 1$. Thus, if $f(t) = X^t - 1$, if the given ideal is generated by $f(m), f(n)$ where $m < n$ without loss to generality, then the ideal contains $f(n - k_1m)$, where $k_1$ can be any positive natural number (repeatedly apply the described operation on $f(n)$). It can be easily seen that through repeated application of this technique, we are replicating the steps of using the Euclidean algorithm to determine the gcd of $a, b$. It follows that $X^d - 1$ is necessarily an element of the ideal generated by $X^n - 1$ and $X^m - 1$. 

To complete the proof that the ideal generated by $X^m - 1$ and $X^n - 1$ is equal to the principal ideal generated by $X^d - 1$, we would just have to prove that the principal ideal created by $X^d - 1$ contains $X^m - 1$ and $X^n - 1$. Assume for some constant $k$, $X^{kd} - 1$ is contained inside the ideal generated by $X^d - 1$. It would then follow that $X^{k(d + 1} - X^d + X^d - 1 = X^{k(d + 1)} - 1$ is contained inside this ideal as well. If $n = ad$ and $m = bd$, given $X^d - 1$ is in the ideal generated by $X^d - 1$, so is $X^{2d} - 1$, $X^{3d} - 1$, and continue recursively until we see that both $X^{ad} - 1$ and $X^{bd} - 1$ are contained inside the ideal generated by $X^d - 1$.

Given any ideal generated by $X^a - 1, X^b - 1$ contains $X^d - 1$ and any ideal generated by $X^d - 1$ contains $X^a - 1, X^b - 1$, it follows that the ideal generated by $X^d - 1$ is equal to the ideal generated by $X^a - 1, X^b - 1$.
\end{proof}

\begin{problem}{2.b}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
We are aware from the previous part that $q^d - 1$ is a factor of $q^m - 1, q^n - 1$ given if this were not true, it is not possible that $X^m - 1, X^n - 1$ are contained in the ideal generated by $X^d - 1$. We now need to show that $q^d - 1$ is indeed the greatest common divisor of these two values.

Observe that for any $q^x - 1, q^y - 1$ where $x < y$, observe that
$$
q^y - 1 = q^{y - x}(q^x - 1) + q^{y - x} - 1,
$$
and hence if $f(n) = q^n - 1$, $f(y) = f(y - x) + q^{y - x}f(x)$, which is a step in the Euclidean algorithm. Repeatedly applying this process starting with $q^m - 1$, $q^n - 1$ would yield the value $q^d - 1$ given at each step in this algorithm, the power by which the $q$ is raised to is also undergoing the Euclidean algorithm transformation. This shows that $q^d - 1$ must be the greatest common divisor for $q^n - 1, q^m - 1$.
\end{proof}

\begin{problem}{3}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
For the sake of contradiction, assume a monic polynomial $f \in R[X]$ takes the form
$$
f(x) = x^n + a_{n - 1}x^{n - 1} + ... + a_0
$$
and there exists $k = d^{-1}g \in K$ such that $d, g$ share no prime factors (this condition is well-defined given $R$ is a UFD) and $k \notin R$ such that $f(k) = 0$. it follows that
$$
f(d^{-1}g) = (d^{-1}g)^n + a_{n - 1}(d^{-1}g)^{n - 1} + ... + a_0 = 0.
$$
Given $R$ is commutative, observe that it is possible to distributively multiply every element by $d^n$, which shows that
$$
(g)^n + a_{n - 1}d(g)^{n - 1} + ... + a_0d^n = 0.
$$
The element on the right is a multiple of $d$, and thus the left side should also be a multiple of $d$. It follows that every component of the summation on the left contains $d$ as a factor excluding $g^n$, and we know that $g^n$ does not contain $d$ as a factor given $g, d$ are relatively prime. This shows that the left side of the equation cannot be expressed as a multiple of $d$, which creates a contradiction, proving that if $k \in K$ exists such that $f(k) = 0$, then $k \in R$.
\end{proof}

