\begin{problem}{4.c}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
False.
One example of a UFD but not a PID given is the polynomial ring $\mathbb{Z}[X]$. Consider the ideal $I$ generated by $2, x$, and note that this ideal is maximal (no other ideal can contain all non-zero degree polynomials and all integers of even degree). This means that $R/I$ is a subset of $K$ that contains $R$. However, given $2, x$ is not principally generated, $A \neq D^{-1}R$ for some $D$.
\end{proof}

\begin{problem}{4.d}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
False. 
Let $R$ denote the set of all integers divisible by 2, which forms an integral domain. Then if $D_1$ is the set generated by $1/2$, and if $D_2$ is the set generated by $1/4$, both $D_1^{-1}R$ and $D_2^{-1}R$ would contain the set of all integers and $1/2$, which means that they are identical. Yet, $D_1 \neq D_2$.
\end{proof}

\begin{problem}{5}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
For he sake of contradiction, assume that $f'$ is irreducible in $\mathbb{F}_p[X]$, and $f$ is reducible in $\mathbb{Z}[X]$. It follows that $f'$ has no roots in $\mathbb{F}_p[X]$, while $f$ has at least one root $a$ in $\mathbb{Z}[X]$. Let $f = gh$ for some polynomials $g, h$ of degree at least 1. Note that $g, h$ are also of content 1 because if either polynomials had a common divisor in the coefficients, the resulting polynomial $gh = f$ would also have a content greater than 1.

Then, let $g', h'$ denote the images of $g, h$ in $\mathbb{F}_p[X]$. We must now prove that $g'h' = f'$, which would complete the contradiction on the idea that $f'$ is irreducible. Observe that given $f$ and $f'$ have the same degree, it follows that $f$ has a leading coefficient that is not divisible by $p$, and we conclude that $g, h$ also had such leading coefficients. $g'h'$ must thus have a degree that is identical to that of $f'$, and more specifically the identical leading coefficient. Then, starting at the leading coefficient and going back, one by one using the Newton method, it is possible to see that $g'h'$ generates coefficients that are identical to that of $f'$. We thus conclude he proof.
\end{proof}

\begin{problem}{6}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
Given $R$ is a ring of characteristic $p$, it follows that $pn = 0$ for any $n \in R$. 

Observe that expanding $(a + b)^p$ gives us
$$
(a + b)^p = \sum_{i = 0}^p \binom{p}{i}a^ib^{p - i}
$$
due to commutativity. Note that $\binom{p}{i}$ is always divisible by $p$ for $i \neq 0, p$ because the numerator contains prime $p$ but the denominator, $i!(p - i)!$, will not contain $p$ as a factor. Thus, we know that every term except for $a^p$ and $b^p$ cancel out given $R$ has a characteristic of $p$, thus completing the proof that $a^p + b^p = (a + b)^p$.
\end{proof}


